{
  "style": "IEEE",
  "texts": [
    "The I4.0 revolution has connected manufacturing industries' digital and physical worlds [30].",
    "While the name I40 started predominantly in Europe before spreading throughout the rest of the world, American territories refer to the fourth industrial revolution as \"Smart Manufacturing,\" while Asian countries refer to \"Smart factories\" [31,32].",
    "Although the manufacturing industries stand to gain a great deal from deploying I4.0 technologies with all its advantages, there have been general concerns about the possibility of low-skilled workers losing their jobs due to the increased degree of automation, which could lead to an imbalance in the economy and increased social inequality [33].As the I4.0 concept is taking root, a new revolution has been introduced to the industry since 2021, the industry 5.0 (I5.0) [8].",
    "I5.0 uses technological principles introduced by its predecessor, I4.0, to achieve sustainable production processes while emphasizing societal goals that promote human beings' benefits (from operators to consumers) and protect the planet's ecosystem [34].",
    "I5.0 aims to return human beings to the center of innovation and improve human-to-machine collaboration [30]."
  ],
